{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-puzzle-js","path":"/puzzles/easy/22","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h2>Question</h2>\n<p>Without explicitly calculating, find out which is bigger: e^Pi or Pi^e?</p>\n<h2>Hint</h2>\n<h2>Answer</h2>\n<p>e^Pi</p>\n<h2>Solution</h2>\n<p>This is a common placement test question. Since e^x = 1 + x…., we have e^x>1+x. Now, conveneintly choosing x = (Pi / e -1) and solving, we get e^Pi > Pi^e.</p>\n<p>Another way is to observe for f(x) = x^(1/x), differentiating: f'(x) = f(x) * (1/x^2) * (1- ln x);  f is decreasing for x > e so pi^(1/pi) &#x3C; e^(1/e); hence e^(pi)> pi^(e)</p>\n<p>Another approach is to assume e^Pi > Pi^e &#x3C;=> Pi * ln e > e * ln Pi &#x3C;=> ln e/e > lnPi/Pi. Now, notice that f(x) = lnx/x is decreasing function since f'(x) is negative in range <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>e</mi><mo>&#x3C;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&#x3C;</mo><mi>π</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(e&#x3C;x&#x3C;\\pi)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&#x3C;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&#x3C;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></span>, hence above assumption is true!</p>","frontmatter":{"puzzleId":22,"difficulty":"easy","category":"general","title":"e^Pi or Pi^e"}}},"pageContext":{"puzzleId":22,"previousPuzzleRoute":"/puzzles/easy/21","nextPuzzleRoute":"/puzzles/easy/23","difficulty":"easy"}},"staticQueryHashes":["3649515864"],"slicesMap":{}}